<HEAD>

<TITLE>INIS at a Glance - Philosophy</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Stanik Zsolt">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="glance.htm"><IMG SRC="../graphic/glance.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
 <FONT SIZE=6>INIS Philosophy</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<IMG SRC="../graphic/policy.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 VSPACE=30 HSAPCE=20>
<FONT SIZE=3>The basis of INIS is international co-operation.
It is the first international information system in which both
the collection of input and the dissemination of output to users
are decentralized. Only the data processing and output production
are centralized in the INIS Secretariat. This decentralized approach
to input and output was selected because it results in the most
comprehensive coverage of the nuclear literature, the most effective
method of handling information in different languages, and the
most satisfactory services for users of the information.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The design of the International Nuclear Information System has
its origins in a particular philosophy recognized by the original
planners of the System and subsequent operators as being beneficial
for an international system operating under the auspices of a
UN organization. This philosopy can be considered to have a number
of facets:
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
(1) <B>Mission oriented approach</B> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The mission of INIS, as explained in greater detail in the <A HREF="glanmis.htm">Mission</A>
Section, is to provide information on nuclear literature published
throughout the world on the peaceful applications of nuclear science
and technology.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
(2) <B>Decentralized operation</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The roles played by participating Member States are critical for
the operation of the System. The national literature published
within the boundary of each Member State (country) or organizational
confines if an international body is to be scanned, indexed, abstracted,
and described bibliographically for input to INIS by a designated
national centre in each Member. The input thus prepared is sent
to INIS Headquarters at the IAEA in Vienna where it is merged,
checked, corrected and the output products prepared. The output
products covering the full file are then returned to the individual
Members who are responsible for the provision of nuclear information
services to users within their national boundaries or organizational
confines. This decentralized approach (see <A HREF="../products/fulltext/schemati.htm">schematic</A>)
results in a more comprehensive coverage of the nuclear literature,
is more effective for handling information in different languages
and is instrumental in spreading the cost for operation of the
system in a reasonably equitable manner between large and small
producers and users of the literature.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
(3) <B>Specialized document delivery</B> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The INIS system collects the <A HREF="../products/microfic/index.htm">full text of documents</A>
for the so-called non-conventional<B> </B>(grey) literature. The
full text is available in microform and will be made available
in electronic form in the foreseeable future.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
(4) <B>Universality of <A HREF="../products/products.htm">output products</A>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The range of INIS output products includes the printed &quot;Atomindex&quot;
together with its cumulative indexes; the updates to the Database
on magnetic media; the database online from the computer at the
IAEA and other international hosts; the database on CD-ROM, the
full text of non-conventional literature on microfiche; and other
documentation, such as the INIS manuals (INIS Reference Series).
The range of <A HREF="../products/products.htm">output products</A>
enables national centres or individual users to select whichever
product can be most efficiently used within the information infrastructure
existing at the national centre or available to the individual
user.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
(5) <A HREF="../products/training/index.htm">Training and assistance to Members</A>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
An extensive <A HREF="../products/training/index.htm">INIS Training Program</A>
both for input preparation and provision of information services
from the output products has always been a part of the INIS Philosophy.
Further assistance is provided in the form of specialized software
packages, promotional material and execution of projects in the
framework of IAEA Technical Co-operation activities targeted at
improving national information technology infrastructure.</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG src="../graphic/toolbar.gif" usemap="#toolbar" BORDER=0 VSPACE=5>
<MAP name="toolbar"><AREA shape="rect" coords="1,1,125,46" href="../glance/glance.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="127,1,245,45" href="../whatsnew/whatsnew.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="247,1,365,46" href="../products/products.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="368,1,505,46" href="../wwwlinks/links.htm"><AREA shape="default" nohref></MAP></CENTER><CENTER>
