<HEAD>

<TITLE>INIS at a Glance - Mission </TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Laura Roberson">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="glance.htm"><IMG SRC="../graphic/glance.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=6>INIS Mission</FONT> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The statutes of the IAEA contain an obligation to further the
exchange of scientific and technical information on all aspects
of the peaceful applicaton of nuclear science and technology.
The INIS system was established with the mission of enabling efficient
and effective transfer of information on literature in the nuclear
area published throughout the world.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The original mission was defined in a statement resulting from
the interpretation of the original 1968 design of the System.
The mission statement was as follows:
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<DL>
<DT>&quot;To produce and disseminate in a decentralized manner
a computer based bibliographic database containing records and
abstracts of the literature produced throughtout the world on
all the peaceful applications of nuclear science and technology
and to collect and make available the full text of those items
not readily available through normal commercial channels&quot;
<BR>
whereby &quot;..... all the peaceful applications of nuclear science
and technology....&quot; has always been interpreted to include
also the so-called peripheral areas, such as nuclear applications
in Chemistry, Medicine, Life Sciences, Agriculture, etc. <BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../graphic/collage.gif" BORDER=0></CENTER> 
<BR>
A changing information technology environment together with increased
financial constraints and the need to eliminate duplication and
reduce costs led a recent meeting of the Advisory Committee for
INIS to propose an amended statement of the INIS mission which
reads:
</DL>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>&quot;INIS will respond to the information needs of the International
Nuclear Community by providing in a decentralized manner a comprehensive
information service in the areas of interest and activities of
the IAEA. This will be achieved by:</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<DL>
<DT>- continuing to build a high quality bibliographic database
for the nuclear<BR>
literature;<BR>
- providing full text of the non-conventional part of the above
literature;<BR>
- providing mechanisms to facilitate access to bibliographic information
<BR>
and full text of nuclear related literature available elsewhere;
<BR>
- providing mechanisms to access other types of nuclear information.&quot;
<BR>
On the basis of this new mission statement the provision of nuclear
information will rely on a dual approach; the concurrent existence
of a high quality database created by INIS as well as the use
of up-to-date tele-networking technology for accessing nuclear
information available elsewhere. Similar technologies can also
provide access to the full text of relevant nuclear literature.
INIS operations based on the new mission statement are in the
early development stages.<BR>
<BR>

</DL>

<P>
<CENTER> <IMG src="../graphic/toolbar.gif" usemap="#toolbar" BORDER=0 VSPACE=5>
<MAP name="toolbar"><AREA shape="rect" coords="1,1,125,46" href="../glance/glance.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="127,1,245,45" href="../whatsnew/whatsnew.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="247,1,365,46" href="../products/products.htm"><AREA shape="rect" coords="368,1,505,46" href="../wwwlinks/links.htm"><AREA shape="default" nohref></MAP></CENTER><CENTER>
