<HEAD>

<TITLE>INIS at a Glance - Policy/Advisory Groups</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Laura Roberson">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="glance.htm"><IMG SRC="../graphic/glance.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=6>INIS Policy/Advisory Groups</FONT> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<IMG SRC="../graphic/phil.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"> <A HREF="../liaison/liaison.htm">INIS Liaison Officers</A>
play a key role in the INIS system. Liaison Officers are the official
representatives of participating INIS member countries and/or
international organizations. They provide the Secretariat with
advice on matters relating to the administration, operation, and
development of INIS. They are responsible for organizing the collection of information in their
country and for the preparation of input from their country or
international organization. They are also responsible for the
dissemination of INIS products through their information services
and for encouraging their utilization.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The INIS Liaison Officers provide the <A HREF="glansec.htm">INIS Secretariat</A>
with advice on matters relating to the administration, operation,
and development of INIS. Regular communication takes place by
correspondence and through the Annual Consultative Meetings of
the INIS Liaison Officers. Proceedings of these meetings contain
the findings and recommendations of the Liaison Officers; this
feedback is always given very serious consideration by the INIS
Secretariat. An important contributing factor to the success
of INIS has been the spirit of mutual understanding and co-operation
that has developed among individual Liaison Officers, the Liaison
Officers as a group, and the INIS staff at the IAEA.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
INIS also receives advise from the INIS Advisory Committee who
reports to the Director General of the IAEA. The Committee includes
producers, users, and administrators of information organizations,
has a broad geographical distribution and represents the interests
of developing countries. Major policy and budgetary matters are
referred to this Committee.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
All aspects of the changed environment under which INIS has to
operate were reviewed by the 9th Advisory Committee for INIS held
in November-December 1994. Prior to the meeting several actions
were initiated including the carrying out of a User Needs Study
and a Subject Search Study, and the drafting of &quot;Strategic
Guidelines for INIS Developments 1995-2000&quot; including its
evaluation by a group of INIS consultants. In particular, the
Committee discussed the changed role that INIS can play as the
source of information to fulfil the statutory requirement of the
IAEA. The Committee has recommended that access to nuclear information
would be ensured not only by producing the INIS Database as it
has been in the past, but also that access to bibliographic information
and full text documents available elsewhere would become part
of the overall INIS approach to the provision of nuclear information.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG src="../graphic/toolbar.gif" usemap="#toolbar" BORDER=0 VSPACE=5>
