<H3><A NAME="INIS_COMMEMORATES">INIS COMMEMORATES TWENTY-FIVE
YEARS OF SUCCESSFUL SERVICES </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>In May 1970 the first electronic and printed products of INIS
were distributed to Member States of the IAEA. INIS, as a co-operative
programme between the Secretariat at the IAEA and the participating
Member States, was established. It was proved through the years
to be one of the most effective tools for the international exchange
of information relating to the peaceful uses of atomic energy.
<BR>
The INIS Members commemorated the silver anniversary through use
of different media such as press releases, articles in information
and scientific journals, booklets, announcements on hosts, advertising
in information journals, exhibitions, etc. The INIS Secretariat
produced various promotional articles for use by INIS Members.
<BR>
The 1995 meeting of INIS Liaison Officers also commemorated the
Twenty Fifth Anniversary. IAEA Director General, Dr. Hans Blix
delivered the opening address. He presented a brief review of
the establishment of INIS, emphasizing the novel aspect of decentralization
in both input preparation and information dissemination. He also
stressed the current importance of INIS in exchange of information
in peaceful uses of atomic energy.<BR>
Papers especially prepared for the Twenty Fifth Anniversary portion
of the meeting programme were presented by four invited keynote
speakers, Mr. E. Brunenkant, former Director of the IAEA's Division
of Scientific and Technical Information, Mr. B. Mahon, Executive
Director of EUSIDIC, Ms. T.C. Rumsey, Director of the Office of
Science, Education and Technical Information of the United States
Department of Energy and Mr. V. Terent'ev, Director of ATOMINFORM,
Moscow, Russian Federation.<BR>
INIS is the largest of the electronic databases created by the
IAEA in co-operation with its Member States. Its continuing success
reflects the active support and participation of IAEA Member States.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="INIS_STRATEGIC_STUDY">INIS STRATEGIC STUDY </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>At the 1994 Consultative Meeting of INIS Liaison Officers,
it was noted that during the past 25 years the information environment
has changed, information technology and electronic data exchange
have been revolutionized, the economics of information services
at the National Centers have changed, and the role of nuclear
energy has altered.<BR>
The needs for nuclear information are also different from those
originally envisaged. All of these factors, coinciding with the
25th anniversary of INIS and the approach of the 21st century,
led to a recommendation for a strategic review of the overall
objectives and operations of INIS.<BR>
It was recommended that the INIS Secretariat conduct a Strategic
Study that would bring the organization into line with current
and anticipated developments in information technology. The Secretariat
contracted for this study in mid 1994, and the results, <U>Strategic
Guidelines for INIS Developments 1995-2000</U>, were presented
to the 9th Advisory Committee for INIS, which met in Vienna, 29
November - 1 December 1994.<BR>
The Advisory Committee, after reviewing the recommendations of
the strategic study, and comparing the original ideas for the
creation of INIS to current and anticipated requirements, drafted
a new mission statement for INIS whose essential points are that
INIS:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>Continue to build high quality bibliographic databases for
the nuclear literature;
<LI>Provide full text of the non-conventional part of the above
literature; and
<LI>Provide mechanisms to facilitate access to bibliographic information
and full text of nuclear related literature available elsewhere.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>This broad strategic guidance was based on:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>Changes over the past 25 years in the scope of information
that is relevant to the IAEA and Member States;
<LI>New philosophies in information and library services, especially
those regarding &quot;ownership vs. timely access;&quot;
<LI>Significant new technologies that support the mission statement.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>Strategic developments will result in a variety of new actions
and services by the INIS Secretariat and Member States. These
will include:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>Re-evaluation of the scope of information that should be included
in the INIS database;
<LI>Upgrading current IAEA/INIS computer and telecommunications
technology to increase productivity of Member States;
<LI>Making the INIS database available for electronic downloading
by FTP and by distribution on CD-ROM at a fraction of current
prices;
<LI>Production of full text in an electronic format for further
dissemination by a variety of media; and
<LI>Formation of partnerships with other organizations in order
to share information of mutual interest, and to provide gateways
to remote databases.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>Operationally, INIS has already begun to implement many of
these developments. These include an ongoing comparison of database
content to IAEA areas of interest, a requirements study for an
enhanced FIBRE and eventual INIS Work Station, implementation
of an INIS Internet World Wide Web home page with links to other
nuclear sites of interest, development of a full text imaging
capability and dissemination of NCL on CD-ROM and other media,
and initiation of partnerships with scientific publishers and
database organizations.<BR>
A variety of other changes, outlined in the strategic guidelines,
and by the INIS Advisory, Technical and Consultative Committees,
will be implemented in the next several years in order to assure
that INIS and Members are able to take full advantages of emerging
information technologies.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="The_24th_MEETING">24th MEETING OF INIS LIAISON OFFICERS,
KYOTO, MAY 1996 </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>At the invitation of the government of Japan, the Twenty-fourth
Consultative Meeting of INIS Liaison Officers was held in Kyoto,
Japan in the final week of May. The Meeting marked the twenty-fifth
anniversary of INIS activities in Japan and aroused considerable
media interest - the opening session was even featured on a national
television news programme. Forty-nine participants representing
forty-seven countries and two international organizations and
a number of observers attended.<BR>
Discussions at the Consultative Meeting of INIS Liaison Officers
covered a wide range of topics and were very fruitful, providing
the INIS Secretariat with guidance on a number of key issues.
In particular, the Liaison Officers considered several points
connected with the framework for Strategic Guidelines for INIS
developments adopted in 1995. The recom-mendations of the Meeting
will influence future enhancements of the FIBRE software and the
PC-based training package and will also help the Secretariat to
finalize work on the preparation of the INIS Home Page. Other
areas considered include the possible redefinition of the INIS
subject scope, especially in some areas of &quot;basic&quot; science,
and the inclusion in the database of records from other sources.
With regard to this final topic, the Liaison Officers recommended
strongly that records from other sources be adapted to conform
fully to INIS rules; this decision is a strong vindication of
the high quality of the INIS database. Further details of the
discussions on these and other topics are to be found in the Report
of the Proceedings, previously distributed to all INIS Liaison
Officers.<BR>
In conjunction with the Meeting of INIS Liaison Officers, three
additional &quot;satellite&quot; meetings were held. One of these
was attended by representatives of &quot;large&quot; inputting
centres and aimed to identify more cost-effective ways for these
centres to input information to the database. The other meetings
were for representatives of countries participating in one of
the IAEA regional Technical Co-operation Projects RAS/0/019 or
RER/0/011 to upgrade the nuclear information systems in East Asia
and the Pacific and Europe. Again, details of these meetings have
been presented separately.<BR>
In addition to the discussions and scientific visits to the Nara
Institute of Science and Technology and Broadband - ISDN Business
Chance and Culture Creation, participants and observers enjoyed
a full programme of social and sightseeing events arranged by
our Japanese hosts, highlights of which included trips to the
Todai-ji and Horyu-ji temples in Nara. Evening receptions provided
a welcome chance to chat socially with old friends while sampling
the delights of Japanese cuisine. Our thanks are due to the staff
of the Japanese National INIS Centre, especially to the Liaison
Officer Mr N. Hiramatsu, for all they did to make our time in
Japan so pleasurable.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="INIS_CONTINUES">INIS CONTINUES TO EMBRACE NEW INFORMATION
TECHNOLOGY </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>INIS, from its inception almost 26 years ago, embraced computer
technology for maximizing information management. The INIS Secretariat
has continued through the years to use computer-based technology
for both input and output of INIS operations, products and services.
This tradition continues with the embracing of new information
technologies available on the Internet. During 1996, INIS has
been developing a Home Page to disseminate information on the
Internet via the World Wide Web.<BR>
Why an INIS Home Page? Development of an INIS Home Page was recommended
by INIS Liaison Officers in the 1995 Liaison Officer Meeting.
The Home Page, as a new world-wide dissemination media, is perceived
to facilitate a number of objectives, including:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>Provision of INIS information to members;
<LI>Introducing INIS to non-members and the general public;
<LI>Providing an entry point for the INIS database;
<LI>Offering external links to other relevant in-scope INIS type
information; and
<LI>Permitting full text document delivery.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The Main INIS home pages include organizational information,
products and services, database access, external links (including
to INIS Liaison Officers), news, key word search and a guestbook.
The Home Page has a Help Section to assist users in accessing
the Home Page.<BR>
Work began on the Home Page in January, 1996. A prototype was
presented at the May Liaison Officers meeting in Japan. Subsequent
to the Meeting, the prototype went through some revision based
on the ILOs feedback. It is anticipated the feedback from INIS
Liaison Officers will help to improve the Home Page and make this
new dissemination technology useful to the INIS community.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="INIS_DATA_PROCESSING">INIS DATA PROCESSING SYSTEM
(IDPS) </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The development of the new INIS Data Processing System (IDPS)
is a primary development project for INIS for the period 1994-1997.
The goal of the project is migrating from the mainframe technology
to modern Client/Server architecture. The implementation of IDPS
will allow INIS to make better use of human and other resources,
to improve operational efficiency, to simplify maintenance procedures,
to reduce data processing cost and to use paperless technology.
<BR>
IDPS consists of four subsystems:
</DL>

<OL>
<LI>The INIS Authority Maintenance Subsystem which includes Thesaurus
Maintenance Subsystem, Journal Titles Maintenance Subsystem and
Corporate Names Maintenance Subsystem;
<LI>The INIS Record Processing Subsystem (IRPS);
<LI>The INIS Input Registration Subsystem; and
<LI>The INIS Ordering Subsystem.
</OL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The development of the INIS database online retrieval system
and the system for printing INIS products are out of the scope
of the project.<BR>
The new <I>INIS Data Processing System</I> has been developed
on the basis of Client/Server architecture. The server part is
based on a UNIX/C/Sybase environment and an IBM-RISC/6000 computer
has been installed as an INIS Production Server. The client part
is based on a Windows/C/C++/Visual Basic environment.<BR>
The development of the <I>INIS Authority Maintenance</I> <I>Subsystem</I>
has been completed and the Thesaurus Maintenance Subsystem has
been in operation since January 1995. The new system is much friendlier
and faster than the old one, and provides multilingual support.
The rest of the Authority subsystems will be implemented together
with IRPS.<BR>
The <I>INIS Record Processing Subsystem</I> is now under implementation.
The System allows input and correction of INIS records via online
dialog and has a direct link to the Authority Maintenance Subsystem.
An important technical idea implemented in IRPS is to use the
FIBRE checking engine as a core of the new system. FIBRE will
provide all checks on the server and on the clients.<BR>
The <I>INIS Input Registration Subsystem</I> and the <I>INIS Ordering
Subsystem</I> will be developed after implementation of IRPS.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="New_databases">NEW DATABASES AVAILABLE IN 1997 </A>
</H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The INIS bibliographic database will be very soon available
at a significantly reduced price and a new non-conventional literature
(NCL) full-text database on CD-ROM will be available in 1997.
Cost of these databases are not currently determined, but it is
anticipated they will be significantly lower than the cost of
the current database on CD-ROM and NCL microfiche standing order.
<BR>
The bibliographic database will continue to use the SilverPlatter
WINSPIRS software. This will eliminate requirements for new training.
It is expected that production of the database, and quarterly
updates<BR>
with the new price, will commence in early 1997. INIS will produce
six archival CD-ROMs for the bibliographic database which include
one new archival disk<B> </B>for INIS data from 1970 up to 1975,
and a quarterly update<B>.</B> <BR>
The NCL full-text database will contain all (non-US) reports now
disseminated on microfiche.<BR>
US reports will be added in the future. INIS expects to have an
operational imaging capability in early 1997 and dissemination
of the database will begin in the first quarter. Retrieval using
the NCL CD-ROM will be by the report numbers or INIS reference
number. It will eventually be linked to the INIS bibliographic
database. The NCL full-text CD-<BR>
ROM collection will consist initially of approximately 50 CD-ROMs
a year increasing to 150 per year as the US non-conventional literature
is included in the database.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="PC_TRAINING">PC-TRAINING PACKAGE IS BEING TESTED
IN INIS CENTERS </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The INIS Training Program has several objectives, including
improving the quality of the INIS database, better coverage of
INIS subject scope, improvement of INIS services, establishing
and/or improving the national information infrastructure, and
transferring modern information technology. In keeping with these
objectives, the INIS Secretariat has been developing a PC-Based
Training Package for use by INIS members.<BR>
The Training Package is being created with the anticipation of
also achieving several important objectives including:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>Providing efficient and cost effective training within INIS
Centers;
<LI>Providing an on-site self-teaching tool;
<LI>Allowing individuals to learn at their own pace;
<LI>Broadening the availability of training to all INIS members;
<LI>Utilizing multi-media, multilingual, multi-senses techniques
to enhance learning; and
<LI>Facilitating the process for learning INIS input procedures
at the point of need within an INIS Centre.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The INIS PC-Based Training Package has four sections and a
Coursebook.<BR>
The sections include:
</DL>

<UL>
<LI>How to Use the PC-Based Training Package;
<LI>Introducing INIS (a 10 minute promotional tool which has sound
and can be used as a &quot;rolling demo&quot; for INIS promotion
at conferences, meetings, etc.);
<LI>Subject Analysis; and
<LI>Bibliographic Description.
</UL>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The Coursebook includes examples of case studies for post
tests and a feedback form. Teaching techniques and capabilities
in the Package include, for example, questioning techniques, practice
ability; glossary; highlighting; voice off/on; stated objectives
by module and function buttons.<BR>
The PC-Based Training Package will be output on a CD-ROM. For
use, it will require a 486 PC with 3.1 Windows or higher, a graphics
card capable of 640*480*64000 colours, 8MB RAM and a mouse. Each
INIS Centre will be provided a copy of the final CD-ROM and Coursebook.
<BR>
The Package was presented for review by INIS Liaison Officers
at the May Liaison Officers Meeting in Japan. It is currently
being tested and evaluated by INIS Centres. The Secretariat expects
to issue the final version to INIS members by January, 1997. Review
and feedback from INIS Centres is expected to help validate and
improve the Training Package.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="WinFIBRE_and_requirements">WinFIBRE AND REQUIREMENTS
OF FIBRE </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>In 1995/1996 the INIS Secretariat continued the development
of the FIBRE (Friendly Inputting of Bibliographic Records) software.
In particular, following requests made by INIS National Centres,
the Windows version of FIBRE has been developed and distributed
to INIS inputting centres.<BR>
The FIBRE package consists of several modules: checking engine,
interface, authority viewer, authority files, files with checking
rules and matrixes, and help files. During the development of
WinFIBRE only the FIBRE interface and authority viewer have been
fully redesigned. It means that WinFIBRE uses the same checking
engine and the same data files (user defined matrixes, authority
files, format description files, cross checking rules files, and
spelling checker files) as DOS FIBRE 2.1. and, therefore, WinFIBRE
is fully compatible with DOS FIBRE.<BR>
WinFIBRE interface looks and acts like any other program that
runs under Microsoft Windows&#153;.<BR>
The screen layout, dialogs, menus, shortcut keys, and toolbars
are different, however, from those of the DOS FIBRE 2.1 version.
<I>DOS FIBRE users should treat WinFIBRE as a new program that
does everything FIBRE 2.1 could do but in a Windows-standard way.</I>
WinFIBRE has a Windows standard Multiple Document Interface (MDI)
and during an edit session more than one input file can be opened
at a time. Users can also change the types and sizes of font,
send files with prepared INIS records directly from WinFIBRE as
an attachment to MS E-mail, and exchange information with other
Windows applications using copy and paste functions.<BR>
Some of the WinFIBRE modules can be used independently on WinFIBRE.
In particular users can run the WinFIBRE authority viewer to consult
INIS authorities and load WinFIBRE help file to consult electronic
versions of both <I>WinFibre User's Manual</I> and <I>Guide of
Bibliographic Description (IAEA-INIS-1). <BR>
</I>The development of the WinFIBRE software was done in close
co-operation with INIS National Centres which have provided very
important ideas and suggestions. The WinFIBRE user's manual has
been prepared by the Canadian INIS Centre and WinFIBRE Help has
been improved by Bulgarian and Belorussian INIS Centres.<BR>
Hardware and software requirements for running WinFIBRE:<BR>
<B>Computer</B>: IBM PC or compatible computer capable of running
Microsoft Windows&#153;.<BR>
<B>Memory:</B> Minimum 4MB of RAM (random access memory).<BR>
<B>Hard disk</B>: Slightly under 7 MB of space<B>. <BR>
Monitor</B>
</DL>

<P>
: VGA or higher.<BR>
<B>Operating system: </B>Microsoft Windows&#153; version 3.1 or
3.11.<BR>
<B>Floppy disk drive:</B> Send input to the INIS Secretariat on
5.25 inch or 3.5 inch disks.<BR>
<B>Mouse</B>: A mouse is almost essential, although it is possible
to do most things with keystrokes 
<H3><A NAME="INIS_information">INIS INFORMATION ACCESSIBLE VIA
FTP AND EMAIL </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>To facilitate and expedite the delivery of INIS information,
the INIS Secretariat has an Internet FTP server to distribute
information (i.e. INIS Reference Manuals, INIS Atomindex files,
and INIS Authorities). Information on this server is updated frequently,
i.e. every two weeks and after each production cycle, a new INIS
Atomindex file is added on the FTP server and INIS Members are
informed accordingly. INIS Authorities as well as INIS Reference
Manuals are also updated accordingly and made available to Members.
For those INIS Centres which do not have FTP facilities, the INIS
Secretariat sends INIS Atomindex files and INIS Authorities as
an attachment to email message. Both services are proving to be
very useful to INIS Members.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="NEA_computer">NEA COMPUTER PROGRAM SERVICE SUPPORTED
BY INIS </A></H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The OECD Nuclear Energy Agency Data Bank (NEADB) operates
a computer program service related to nuclear energy and technology
applications. The software library collects programs and upon
receipt of requests from users, verifies them in an appropriate
computer environment ensuring that the computer program package
is complete and adequately documented. The material is then distributed
to users. This collection of tested material contains more than
1600 packages. Standard software verification procedures are used
following an ANSI/ANS standard. A co-operative arrangement in
this field has been established with the IAEA. As support for
this service, Mr. Juan Galan, staff member of the INIS CSU is
located at the NEA in Paris working directly with the Data Bank
Program. INIS also provides the IAEA Liaison Officer for this
service.<BR>
An on-line search service for computer program abstracts is available
on Internet. (http://www.nea.fr/html/dbprog.html). Programs are
dispatched to users by network, magnetic tape, diskette, cartridges
or CD-ROM.<BR>
The NEADB distributes to and acquires computer codes from more
than 500 accredited institutions from its 19 member countries
and from another 65 IAEA member countries. Institutions are entitled
to use the service after approval from their national authorities.
The institutions from IAEA member countries have to contact, through
their national authorities, the Permanent Mission of their country
to the IAEA in Vienna. The Permanent Mission will then contact
the Director General of IAEA informing him of the desired participation,
and at the same time the Permanent Mission should nominate someone
to act as a liaison officer between the establishment and the
NEADB.<BR>
Every year about 150 new computer programs or versions are acquired.
More than 25,000 computer program packages have been sent out
to requesters since the beginning of this service in 1964 of which
about 4500 were sent to non-OECD countries. The annual total distribution
during the last few years was on the average more than 1500. Fifty
percent of the requests were sent in recent years to governmental
laboratories or agencies; thirty percent went to universities
and the other twenty percent to industry and utilities.<BR>
As a rule, programs are provided for non-profit research studies.
The agreement of the originating establishment must be obtained
before a service is offered involving use on a fee-paying basis
of any program distributed by the Data Bank. This restriction
also applies to modified versions derived from program copies
obtained from the NEADB.<BR>
Transfer of a program to a user in a given establishment confers
only the right to use the program within that organisation; in
particular, copies of programs should not be distributed to persons
outside their own establishment..
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="INIS_video">INIS VIDEOFILM UNDER PRODUCTION </A>
</H3>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>Following the recommendation of the INIS Liaison Officers,
the INIS Secretariat has begun production of a new INIS promotional
film. The present videofilm, produced about 9 years ago and considered
by the INIS National Centres as a very efficient promotion tool,
is obsolete. The need for the replacement has been expressed many
times by INIS Member States.<BR>
In 1995, the INIS Secretariat contracted the National Technical
Information Centre and Library (OMIKK), Budapest, Hungary for
the film production. The English version of the film is expected
to be ready for distribution by the 25th Consultative Meeting
of INIS Liaison Officers in May 1997.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="New_promotional">NEW PROMOTIONAL PUBLICATIONS AVAILABLE
</A></H3>

<H4>&quot;Presenting INIS&quot; </H4>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>A revision of &quot;Presenting INIS&quot; in English is now
available in printed form free-of-charge from the Centre Services
Unit. The publication is also available on the INIS Home Page
as a PDF file.<BR>
This 48-page, illustrated booklet describes the history of INIS,
its philosophy, INIS operation, output products and services through
the IAEA, other major hosts and database providers, through national
or in-house systems and the Computer Program Service of the Nuclear
Energy Agency (NEA) of the OECD. [see pages 35-47 for a list of
INIS Liaison Officers for INIS Member States and co-operating
international organizations and pages 31-34 for a list of contact
addresses where to order INIS products or write for further information].
</DL>

<H4>&quot;INIS Periodic Report - 1995&quot; </H4>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The second issue of the &quot;INIS Periodic Report&quot;,
a new INIS promotional publication including the INIS 25th Anniversary
edition, was published in May 1996. The attractive 24-page colour
booklet presents the highlights of INIS operations in 1995 in
INIS Members: promotion and marketing output products and services,
international contacts, important changes in INIS Members, training,
introduction of new INIS Members, status of the INIS database
in 1995, and products and services in Member States. The new INIS
Mission Statement is given as approved by the 9th Advisory Committee
for INIS and by Member States at the 23rd Consultative Meeting
of INIS Liaison Officers in 1995. Activities of INIS Members in
celebrating the 25th anniversary of INIS are described. A supplement
to the Report &quot;Development of INIS&quot; contains details
on the history of INIS. The Report including the supplement is
available free-of-charge from the Centre Services Unit. It is
also on the INIS Home Page as a PDF file.
</DL>

<H3><A NAME="Reference_series">REFERENCE SERIES HAS REVISED AND
NEW MANUALS </A></H3>

<H4>IAEA-INIS-12 (Rev. 3) INIS: Manual for Subject Analysis </H4>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The Subject Analysis manual, published in January 1996 replacing
the <I>INIS: Manual for Indexing, IAEA-INIS-12 (Rev. 2),</I> is
a result of one year's co-operative work between INIS and the
Energy Technology Data Exchange (ETDE). The concept and structure
of the new manual is intended to describe in a logical and efficient
sequence all the steps comprising the subject analysis of documents
to be reported to INIS and ETDE. The manual includes new chapters
on preparatory analysis, subject classification, abstracting and
subject indexing, as well as rules, guidelines, procedures, examples
and a special chapter on Guidelines and Examples for Subject Analysis
in Particular Subject Fields. The chapter on Subject Indexing
is based on the previous version of the Manual; however, substantial
changes related to subject analysis since its publication in 1974
are reflected in the new Manual. The Manual is available from
the Sales and Promotion Unit of the IAEA at a price of 200 Austrian
Schillings and also on the IAEA FTP server.
</DL>

<H4>IAEA-INIS-23 FIBRE Users' Manual </H4>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>This is a new publication in the INIS Reference Series released
in February 1995 that provides the information needed by the INIS
input centres to prepare and submit records to INIS using the
software FIBRE (<U>F</U>riendly <U>I</U>nputting of <U>B</U>ibliographic
<U>R</U>ecords). Besides an introduction of FIBRE and instruction
on how to install and set up FIBRE, the Manual describes how to
use FIBRE to prepare bibliographic input, discusses its use for
subject indexing, checking input and making a file to send to
the INIS Secretariat. The Manual is available from the Sales and
Promotion Unit of the IAEA at a price of 200 Austrian Schillings
and also on the IAEA FTP server.
</DL>

<H4>IAEA-INIS-2 (Rev. 7) INIS: Samples for Bibliographic Description
</H4>

<DL>
<DT>
<DD>The seventh revision of the Samples, a companion volume to
<I>IAEA-INIS-1 (Rev. 8) INIS: Guide to Bibliographic Description,</I>
was published in September 1996. The samples are presented in
the FIBRE format as this software is widely used throughout the
INIS community. The publication is available from the Sales and
Promotion Unit of the IAEA at a price of 100 Austrian Schillings
and also on the IAEA FTP server.
</DL>

