18:00 - <b>Keynote presentation on results of major projects of
Japan with Belarus, the Russian Federation and
Ukraine</b><BR><I>K. Kiikuni, Executive Managing Director,
Sasakawa Memorial Health Foundation, Japan</i>
<P>
18:20 - <b>Keynote presentation on results of major projects of
the USA with Belarus, the Russian Federation and
Ukraine</b><BR><I>S. Galson, Chief Medical Officer of
Environment, Safety and Health, USA </i> 

<P>
<HR>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="tech">
WEDNESDAY, April 10th 1996</A> <P>

<center>TECHNICAL SYMPOSIUM<P></STRONG></center>
The Technical Symposium will comprise:
<UL>
<LI>Eight distinct <I> Topical Sessions</i> covering the major
Conference topics; these will be based on scientific
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/chernobyl/abstract.html"><B>background papers</B></A> prepared in
advance by committees of senior scientists; 
<LI>A <i>Poster Session</i> in which the <b>individual papers
</b>submitted to the Conference will be displayed and discussed:
and
<LI>A<I> Concluding Session</i> where the technical
<B>conclusions and recommendations</B> of the Symposium will be
summarized by the Conference President.
</UL>
<P>
<b>Topical Sessions</B><P>
9:00 - <B>Topical Session 1: Clinically observed effects</B><br>
<B>Chairperson: </B><I>F.Mettler, University of New Mexico,
USA</i><BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson: </B><I>A. Guskova, Institute of Biophysics,
Russian Federation</i><BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary: </B> <I>Dr. G. Souchkevitch, WHO</i><br>
<B>Rapporteur: </b><I>G. Wagemaker, Erasmus University,
EC<Br></I>
<B>Expert committee:</b> <I>Dr. V. Bebeshko, Scientific Centre of
Radiation Medicine, Ukraine<BR>
Dr. N. Griffiths, Insitut de Protection et de Sret Nuclaire,
France<BR>
Prof. A. Guskova, Institute of Biophysics, Russian Federation<BR>
Dr. N. Krysenko, Deputy Minister of Health, Belarus</I>
<P>

The topics to be addressed at this session include:<P>
<UL>
     <LI>the definitive numbers and the severity of the
deterministic effects; and
<LI> results and conclusions of studies on occupationally exposed
workers (including the emergency workers known as
<I>liquidators</i>), covering both doses received and effects
incurred (including diagnosis, attributability to radiation as
cause, treatment and longer term follow-up).
</ul>

<P>


11:00 - <B>Topical Session 2:  Thyroid effects
<BR>
Chairperson: </B><I>Prof. A. Pinchera, University of Pisa,
Italy</i><BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson: </B><I> Prof. N.D. Tronko, Institute of
Endocrinology and Metabolism, Ukraine</i><BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary: </B> <I>Dr. A. Karaoglou, European
Commission, Belgium</i><BR>
<B>Rapporteur: </B><I> Prof. Sir E.D. Williams, Cambridge
University, UK</i><BR>
<B>Expert committee: </B> <I>Prof. D. Becker, Cornell Medical
Centre, USA<BR>
Prof. E.P. Demidchik, State Medical Institute, Belarus<BR>
Prof. S. Nagataki, Nagasaki University School of Medicine,
Japan<BR> 
Prof. A. Pinchera, University of Pisa, Italy<BR>
Prof. N.D. Tronko, Institute of Endocrinology and Metabolism,
Ukraine</i>
<P>
<UL>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:<P>
<LI> the best estimates of thyroid dose distribution by area and
age, and their accuracy;
<LI> effects of radiation on thyroid function;
<LI> spontaneously occurring thyroid effects
<LI> reporting, diagnosis, treatment and follow-up;
<LI> pathology and molecular characterization of thyroid cancers;
<LI> definitive estimates of thyroid cancer in children and
adults in Belarus, Ukraine and the Russian Federation;
<LI> attributability of thyroid effects to radiation doses and
confounding factors;
<LI> conclusions of epidemiological studies; and
<LI> estimated future effects.
</ul>
<p>
14:00 -<B> Topical Session 3:  Longer term health effects<br>

Chairperson: </B><I>Prof. R.H.Clarke, Director, National
Radiological Protection Board, UK</i><br>
<b>Vice-Chairperson:</b><I> Prof. A. Okeanov,Centre for Medical
Technology, Belarus</i><br> 
<B>Scientific Secretary:</B> <I>R. Schmidt, WHO</I><BR>

<B>Rapporteur: </B><I>Dr. E. Cardis, International Agency for
Research on Cancer, France</I><BR>
<B>Expert committee: </B><I>Dr. L. Anspaugh, Lawrence Livermore
National Lab., USA
<BR>
Prof. V. Ivanov, Medical Radiological Research Centre, Russia
<BR>
Prof. I. Likhtariev, Institute of Radiation Medicine, Ukraine
<BR>
Dr. K. Mabuchi, Radiation Effects Research Foundation, Japan
<BR>
Prof. A. Okeanov, Centre for Medical Technology, Belarus
<BR>
Prof. A. Prisyazhniuk, Scientific Centre for Radiation Medicine,
Ukraine</i><P>

The topics to be addressed at this session include:<P>
<UL>
<LI> methods of dose reconstruction and their accuracy, and whole
body measurements;
<LI> best estimates of dose distribution by area and age, and
their accuracy;
<LI> epidemiological and theoretical estimates of induction of
malignancies and hereditary disorders - numbers, severity and
time profile, including effects among<I> liquidators;</I>
<LI> results of current studies (effects and non-effects),
spontaneous effects, confounding factors;
<LI> likely capabilities and limitations of  epidemiological
studies to accurately detect and quantify effects;
<LI> optimisation of long term follow-up
</ul>
<P>

16:00 - <B>Topical Session 4:  Other health related effects: 
          psychological consequences, stress, anxiety
<BR>
Chairperson: </B><I>Dr. B-M. Drottz-Sjberg, Centre for Risk
Research, Sweden</i><br>
<B>Vice-Chairperson: </b><I>Prof. I. Rolevich, First Deputy
Minister for Emergencies, Belarus</i><BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary:</b> <I>H. Kaltenecker, UNESCO</i><BR>

<B>Rapporteur :</b> <I>Prof. T. Lee, University of St. Andrews,
Scotland</i><br>
<B>Expert committee: </b><I>Dr. L.A. Ageeva, Institute of
Sociology, Belarus<br>
Dr. G. Rumyantseva, Institute of General and Forensic Psychiatry,
Moscow, Russian Federation</i><P>

The topics to be addressed at this session include:<P>
<UL>
<LI> psychological consequences among the population and
emergency workers, clinical diagnosis and treatment;
<LI> mental distress and anxiety attributed to the accident
directly or indirectly through perception of the level of
contamination,  the countermeasures taken (evacuation,
resettlement, agricultural countermeasures, etc.), the risk of
other accidents and other factors;
<LI> perception of hazard from initial exposures compared with
that from long term contamination; and
<LI> alleviation of psychological effects.

</ul>



<P>

<center>17:30 <B> PRESS BRIEFING</center></B>
<P>

A Briefing for the Press will be held on the outcome of the first
four Technical Sessions.<P>

<center>17:30 <B>
POSTER SESSION I</center></B>
<P>
<B>Posters of accepted individual papers </b>will be exhibited in
a <B>Poster Hall </B>and individually discussed with authors in
two Poster Sessions at the end of Wednesday and Thursday.  The
full papers will be published in the Conference Proceedings. The
Poster Hall will be open during the entire Conference and visits
will be encouraged. <P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>THURSDAY, 11th April</B>  
<P>
<CENTER>
<B>TECHNICAL SYMPOSIUM</B> (continued)
</CENTER>
<P>
09:00 -  <B>Topical Session 5: Consequences for the
Environment</B>
<BR>
<B>Chairperson:</B> <I>Dr. A. Bouville, National Cancer
Institute, USA</I>
<BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson:</B><I> R. Alexakhin, Russian Federation</I> 
<BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary:</B> <I>Ms. M. Gustafsson, IAEA</I>
<BR>
<B>Rapporteur:</B> <I>Ms. M. Dreicer, USA</I>
<BR>
<B>Expert committee:</B> <I>Dr. A. Aarkrog, Ris&oslash; National
Laboratory,
Denmark</I>
<BR>
<I>R. Alexakhin, Director, Institute of Agricultural Radiology,
Russian Federation
<BR>
Dr. L. R. Anspaugh, Lawrence Livermore National Lab., USA 
<BR>
Prof.   N.P. Arkhipov, Scientific and Technical Centre "Pripyat",
Ukraine 
<BR>
Prof. K-J. Johansson, University of Agricultural Science, Sweden
<BR>
Acad. L.M. Sushchenya, Director, Institute of Zoology, Belarus
</I>
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>effects of radiation versus those of countermeasures;
<LI>effects on flora and fauna and changes to ecosystems due to
radiation and/or countermeasures, risk of genetic damage;
<LI>effects on agriculture, forestry, hunting and fisheries;
<LI>elevated concentrations of radionuclides in environmental
media, including drinking water, hot spots  and  hot particles;
<LI>secondary air contamination (resuspension from fires, surface
water and soil);
<LI>migration of radionuclides;
<LI>potential for hazards to public health and risk to workers
(e.g. agricultural, forestry and industrial workers);
<LI>likely development of relaxation of countermeasures;
<LI>management of contaminated territories, limitations for
future use;
<LI>likely impact of countermeasures - past and proposed. 
<LI>prospects for the 30km exclusion zone;
<LI>criteria for a return to normal, safety of continued
residence; and future prognosis.
</UL>
<P>    
11:00 -   <B>Topical Session 6:  Social, economic, institutional
and political impact</B>
<BR>
<B>Chairperson:</B> <I>Dr. J. Lochard, CEPN, France</I>
<BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson:</B><I> Mr. I. Kenik, Minister for
Emergencies,
Belarus</I>
<BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary:</B> <I>G.N.Kelly, European
Commission</I>
<BR>
<B>Rapporteurs:</B> <I>Mr. V. Kholosha, Minister on Affairs of
Protection
of the Population from the Chernobyl Accident Consequences,
Ukraine 
<BR>
Mr. I. Kenik, Minister for Emergencies, Belarus
<BR>
Mr. V. Vladimirov, Deputy Minister of Emergency Situations,
Russian Federation
</I>
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>changes in life-styles and social framework;
<LI>treating long term health effects in changing social welfare
systems;
<LI>effects of government fiscal policies with regard to
subsidies and compensation;
<LI>industrial development and employment aspects;
<LI>changes in regulatory organization, standards and their
enforcement;
<LI>interaction with general political change in countries of the
former USSR;
<LI>perception of nuclear power, environmental concerns; and
<LI>international co-operation.
</UL>

<P>
14:00  -  <B>Topical Session 6 (continued)</B>
<P>

16:00  -  <B>Topical Session 7: Nuclear safety remedial
measures</B>
<BR>
<B>Chairperson:</B> <I>Mr. L. H&ouml;gberg, Head, Swedish Nuclear
Power
Inspectorate (SKI)</I>
<BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson:</B> <I>Prof. E. Adamov, NIKIET, Russian
Federation</I>
<BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary:</B> <I>L. Lederman, IAEA</I>
<BR>
<B>Rapporteur:</B><I> Prof. A. Birkhofer,  Gesellschaft f&uuml;r
Anlagen
und Reaktorsicherheit, Germany</I>

<P>
There is no expert committee for this session.  Prof. Birkhofer
served as the Chairman of the IAEA/UNDHA International Forum on
One
Decade after Chernobyl: Nuclear Safety Aspects, held on 1 -
3 April 1996, and will report directly the outcome of that Forum,
taking into account the results of other ongoing programmes.
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>improvements in nuclear safety triggered by the accident;
<LI>overview of the results of the IAEA extrabudgetary programme;
<LI>overview of the results of the EC Consortium Project;
<LI>conclusions of the IAEA/UNDHA International Forum on 
One Decade after Chernobyl: Nuclear Safety Aspects held 1-3 April
1996
<LI>state and prospects of the Chernobyl sarcophagus.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER>
17:30  -   <B>POSTER SESSION II</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
Posters of accepted individual papers will be exhibited in a
Poster Hall and individually discussed with authors in two
Poster Sessions at the end of Wednesday and Thursday.  The
full papers will be published in the Conference Proceedings.
The Poster Hall will be open during the entire Conference and
visits will be encouraged.
<P>
<CENTER>
17:30  -   <B>PRESS BRIEFING</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
A Briefing for the Press will be held on the outcome of the
Technical Sessions 5, 6 and 7.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>FRIDAY, 12th April
<P>
<CENTER>
TECHNICAL SYMPOSIUM</B> (continued)
</CENTER>
<P>
09:00  -  <B>Topical Session 8: The Consequences in Perspective:
Prognosis for the future</B>
<BR>

<B>Chairperson:</B> <I>Dr. K. Duncan, UK</I>
<BR>
<B>Vice-Chairperson:</B><I> I. Ponomarenko, Deputy Minister of
Health,
Ukraine</I>
<BR>
<B>Scientific Secretary:</B><I> T. McKenna, IAEA</I>
<BR>
<B>Rapporteur:</B><I> Dr. J-C N&eacute;not, Institut de
Protection
et de
S&ucirc;ret&eacute;
Nucl&eacute;aire, France</I>
<BR>
<B>Expert committee:</B> <I>Dr. A. Prisyazhniuk, Scientific
Centre
for
Radiation Medicine, Ukraine
<BR>
E. Sokolowski, Sweden
<BR>
A. Stavrov, Training, Research and Information Centre, Belarus
<BR>
Dr. P. Waight, Bureau of Radiation and Medical Devices, Canada
</I>
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>comparison of the radiation exposures from the accident with
those due to natural background radiation;
<LI>comparison of numbers of attributable effects with those for
other accidents and other technological and natural disasters,
and with other risks to health common in everyday life; the
question of attributability;
<LI>other public health concerns in countries of the former USSR;
and
<LI>future development of predicted effects.
</UL>
<P>    
10:30  -  <B>Concluding Session </B>
<P>
At the Concluding Session, the technical conclusions and
recommendations of the Technical
Symposium will be summarized by the Conference President.
<DL>
<DD><I>Ms. Angela Merkel, Federal Minister for the Environment,
Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety, Germany</I>
</DL>
<A NAME="panel"><P>
11:00  -  <B>PANEL DISCUSSION:</A> The public's perception of the
Chernobyl accident</B>
<BR>
<I>
Prof. Y. Saenko, Institute of Sociology, Ukraine
<BR>
Dr. J. Harrison, Deputy Director, National Radiological
Protection Board, UK
<BR>
Valeri Gubarev, NECOS Studio, Moscow, Russian Federation
<BR>
Valeri Protchenko, Belarussian State Committee on Television and
Radio, Belarus 
<BR>
Mr. J. Weidemann, Kiev Correspondent of Neue Z&uuml;rcher Zeitung
and Handelsblatt, Germany
<BR>
Mr. Brian Hanrahan, BBC TV, UK
</I>
<P>                                                              
The <I>Panel Discussion</I> will provide an opportunity for
senior representatives of the information media to discuss the
public's perception of the accident's consequences.
<P>
12:30  -  <B>CLOSING SESSION</B>
<P>
A <I>Closing Session</I> will conclude the Conference. 
The Conference President will make <B>keynote closing remarks and
keynote statements</B> presenting the final <B>Conclusions and
Recommendations of the Conference</B>.
<P>
<DL>
<DD>
<I>Ms. Angela Merkel, Federal Minister for the Environment,
Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety, Germany</I>
</DL>
